    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-05-10T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-05-10T01:00:00-05:00" n="18"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d18">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01/5–1049: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Australia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foster</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canberra</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-05-10T16:00:00+10:00"
                            >May 10, 1949—4 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 11—3 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>99. Saw Burton<note n="37" xml:id="d18fn37">John W. Burton, Secretary of the
                        Australian Department of External Affairs.</note> today and urged position
                    outlined Depcirtel May 6, 5 p. m. Burton said Australia planned continue its
                    Embassy in Nanking and had no intention at present recognizing Communists in
                    China. Added however that circumstances might change and that Australia could
                    give no commitments for future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Foster</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
